Now back to the show.

03:15.360 --> 03:19.340
Kevin Knuth, this is an absolute honor, and it's been a long time coming.

03:20.020 --> 03:25.040
You're a physicist at the University of Albany, and to me, you are one of the few people who

03:25.040 --> 03:28.740
speaks about UFOs in a really concrete, hard-headed way.

03:28.820 --> 03:34.140
I think you're one of the few people I know who are studying how these crafts actually fly,

03:34.520 --> 03:38.120
how to detect them, and so I'm really excited to have you.

03:38.200 --> 03:38.460
Thank you.

03:38.500 --> 03:40.240
Wow, and thank you so much for having me.

03:40.380 --> 03:41.180
It's very exciting.

03:41.480 --> 03:42.760
Oh, no, it's an absolute honor.

03:42.760 --> 03:45.900
And you have a NASA background as well.

03:46.320 --> 03:52.520
I want to know how you got into UFOs to begin with, because a lot of people with your sort

03:52.520 --> 03:55.540
of credentials and background think UFOs are a joke.

03:56.980 --> 03:57.800
Right, yeah.

03:57.920 --> 04:01.200
I mean, I've always been interested in UFOs.

04:01.500 --> 04:05.460
I was 12 when Star Wars came out in 1977.

04:05.460 --> 04:10.180
And during that time, I mean, it was the same year Close Encounters, The Third Kind came out.

04:10.620 --> 04:16.360
It was, you know, another movie studio's response to Star Wars that came out in December.

04:16.440 --> 04:20.900
And I didn't like it as much, because there weren't spaceships shooting each other with lasers, right?

04:20.900 --> 04:24.020
You know, so as a 12-year-old, that wasn't that exciting.

04:24.720 --> 04:30.940
But at the same time, you know, there were TV shows like In Search Of with Leonard Nimoy,

04:31.360 --> 04:33.420
and they would cover UFO topics.

04:33.520 --> 04:36.460
And that was on every night, like at 6.30 when we're eating dinner.

04:36.640 --> 04:38.280
So I watched that all the time.

04:38.280 --> 04:40.500
So I've always been interested in them.

04:41.020 --> 04:49.780
And I think I wasn't, so I went to graduate school in 1988.

04:50.500 --> 04:55.820
I grew up in Wisconsin, and I moved out to Montana to go to graduate school at Montana State University

04:55.820 --> 04:56.320
in Bozeman.

04:57.100 --> 05:05.220
And our first week or two there, I had just moved there, and there was a cattle mutilation

05:05.220 --> 05:10.020
where two cows were killed and surgically manipulated.

05:10.300 --> 05:12.500
I don't have a good word for what happened to them.

05:13.140 --> 05:14.300
The blood was drained.

05:14.620 --> 05:15.540
The blood was drained.

05:15.840 --> 05:18.380
The sensory organs removed.

05:18.520 --> 05:19.500
The genitals removed.

05:20.040 --> 05:22.040
One of them had like a core sample.

05:22.160 --> 05:24.480
It had this cylindrical hole punched through it.

05:24.980 --> 05:26.020
Just bizarre.

05:26.200 --> 05:26.900
I mean, really bizarre.

05:27.580 --> 05:31.060
And the people on the news were crazed about this, right?

05:31.100 --> 05:33.720
Oh, my God, there's, you know, these two cows on this ranch were killed.

05:33.720 --> 05:38.460
And there were UFO reports in the county that night, hundreds of reports.

05:38.820 --> 05:43.000
And so the two stories were that it was either aliens or Satanists.

05:43.600 --> 05:46.940
And everybody's all got their undies in a bundle over this, right?

05:47.100 --> 05:52.920
And so we're at the physics department, and some of us grad students are talking about this.

05:53.500 --> 05:58.060
And especially the new graduate students, we've all just moved there into a PhD program.

05:58.160 --> 06:02.260
So you're looking down the barrel of spending five or six years of your life at this place.

06:02.260 --> 06:11.480
And what kind of place did we just move to where cows are murdered this way, right?

06:11.740 --> 06:12.520
This is really bizarre.

06:12.680 --> 06:16.720
So we're discussing this in the hallway, and it was this heated discussion.

06:17.200 --> 06:24.760
And I remember shouting at one point, I don't know why aliens would do it, and I don't know how Satanists would do it.

06:24.760 --> 06:28.760
I mean, it was that level of stupid discussion, right, that students would have.

06:29.160 --> 06:35.880
And we were quite loud and disturbed one of the professors down the hall, and he came out from his office to find out what we're talking about.

06:35.920 --> 06:38.020
He comes down the hall, and we tell him.

06:38.160 --> 06:45.340
And I don't know if he was trying to make us feel better because it was the opposite, but he said, oh, yeah, yeah, this happens from time to time.

06:45.340 --> 06:51.140
And they'll investigate it, and they won't figure anything out, and then everybody will just forget about it until it happens again.

06:52.140 --> 06:53.920
And we're just like, what?

06:54.040 --> 06:58.520
That's even crazier than what we're already talking about.

06:58.960 --> 07:02.000
And then he adds, and he goes, but you know what's really strange?

07:02.700 --> 07:12.480
There are, he goes, I have friends who work up at Malmstrom Air Force Base, and they have problems with UFOs flying over the nuclear missile sites and shutting down nuclear missiles.

07:12.480 --> 07:22.640
And, you know, we listened politely, and when he walked away, we laughed our asses off because this was the, at the time, it was the silliest thing I thought I'd ever heard.

07:22.780 --> 07:29.360
I mean, UFOs are shutting down nuclear missiles, and this isn't, everybody's not on red alert.

07:29.700 --> 07:35.020
I mean, our entire military should be mobilized or something like that, right?

07:35.380 --> 07:36.920
So we just didn't believe it.

07:37.000 --> 07:38.120
We thought this was just silly.

07:38.520 --> 07:40.180
And it became kind of a running joke.

07:40.180 --> 07:47.820
Like, anytime something weird would happen at, you know, at school or somebody's telling a story, oh, this weird thing happened to me, someone would invariably interject.

07:48.160 --> 07:49.280
But you know what's really strange?

07:49.520 --> 07:53.720
UFOs are shutting down nuclear missiles up in Malmstrom Air Force Base, and we would all laugh, right?

07:54.220 --> 07:56.620
And so that was a running joke for a whole year.

07:57.380 --> 08:01.580
And so now time passes, and that was September of 1988.

08:02.760 --> 08:05.560
And he had said that it was ongoing.

08:05.760 --> 08:08.460
He said they are doing this presently, right?

08:08.460 --> 08:17.260
And so now fast forward to, it was about 2015, so it's a couple years before the New York Times article.

08:18.120 --> 08:26.460
And I was teaching an astronomy class, and we got to the point where we were talking about the possibility of life elsewhere.

08:26.960 --> 08:29.620
And some of the students wanted me to comment on UFOs.

08:29.820 --> 08:33.160
I'm like, well, I don't know anything about UFOs, and it's certainly not science.

08:33.160 --> 08:36.980
This is an astronomy class, so I was just poking around on the Internet.

08:37.140 --> 08:43.180
Is there anything reasonable I can actually say other than the Drake equation and the Fermi paradox, right?

08:43.220 --> 08:45.760
The two typical things that scientists might talk about.

08:45.760 --> 09:00.600
And I was just poking around at like 2 a.m., and I stumbled on Robert Hastings' news conference from like 2010, where he had six people on from the Air Force, various Air Force positions.

09:01.200 --> 09:08.060
The first one was Robert Salas talking about UFOs shutting down nuclear missiles at Malmstrom Air Force Base.

09:08.060 --> 09:13.760
And I was like, whoa, whoa, whoa, whoa, whoa, I heard about this in grad school, that was a joke, right?

09:14.100 --> 09:17.860
And then I'm listening to this, I'm like, that's just not a joke.

09:18.080 --> 09:29.160
Between September of 66 and March of 67, we lost 30 missiles to UFO activity.

09:29.380 --> 09:30.880
It's wild, yeah.

09:31.160 --> 09:31.560
30.

09:32.020 --> 09:32.440
30.

09:32.660 --> 09:34.280
That's pretty insane.

09:34.280 --> 09:36.200
Now, now what are you doing?

09:36.200 --> 09:38.560
He's talking about events from 1966.

09:40.120 --> 09:42.100
And I heard about it in 1988.

09:42.600 --> 09:47.200
And the professor that told me in 1988 about this said that it is happening.

09:47.980 --> 09:55.420
So this has been going on for 20 years, and no one's paying any attention to this.

09:56.120 --> 10:01.260
I mean, the Army's still not, the military's still not mobilized and worrying about this.

10:01.260 --> 10:05.000
And I thought, there is something really wrong here.

10:05.960 --> 10:09.000
And I spent some time thinking about it.

10:09.040 --> 10:12.160
I was up late that night teaching class early, right?

10:12.180 --> 10:13.100
I didn't barely sleep.

10:13.460 --> 10:24.800
But I'm thinking about it, and I thought, I mean, it's either nonsense, and the people who are in charge of our nuclear missiles are people we shouldn't be trusting with anything.

10:24.800 --> 10:34.160
Or this is actually real, which makes more sense considering the amount of time that's involved, a 20-year time span.

10:35.040 --> 10:39.660
And nobody's reacting to it, maybe because they all think it's nonsense.

10:39.780 --> 10:41.380
And I thought, this is extremely dangerous.

10:41.780 --> 10:44.920
We're going to get blindsided by something if we're not careful.

10:44.920 --> 10:48.080
And I thought, somebody ought to look into this.

10:48.140 --> 10:50.620
And I thought, I'm going to start looking into this UFO business.

10:50.780 --> 10:52.040
What is here?

10:52.120 --> 10:52.920
How real is this?

10:52.980 --> 10:53.860
How possible is this?

10:53.960 --> 10:56.080
And so that's when I started looking into it.

10:57.380 --> 11:05.400
And I had actually given a talk in our department like a year later after I looked into it somewhat.

11:05.520 --> 11:07.140
I thought, this is actually really interesting.

11:07.140 --> 11:14.360
So I gave a talk in our physics department about it, just an informal talk, and the room was packed.

11:14.720 --> 11:21.340
I mean, I don't know how many people can actually sit in that room, but it was well over the fire limit, right?

11:21.540 --> 11:24.580
I mean, we had people sitting cross-legged right up to the front screen.

11:25.680 --> 11:27.880
And the talk went on.

11:28.040 --> 11:28.940
There were so many questions.

11:29.020 --> 11:30.600
I talked for it for almost three hours.

11:31.220 --> 11:34.620
And most people just stayed for it because everybody was really interested.

11:34.620 --> 11:36.860
And I thought, yeah, see, this is interesting.

11:36.860 --> 11:38.860
I mean, this is an interesting problem here.

11:39.060 --> 11:40.460
And it's not that simple.

11:41.400 --> 11:45.760
And then, of course, a year after that, the New York Times article comes out.

11:46.460 --> 11:50.200
And I thought, well, somebody ought to study this.

11:50.300 --> 11:52.460
And I thought, well, shoot, you just do it.

11:52.960 --> 11:53.560
I should do it.

11:53.940 --> 11:59.220
And the nuclear link, I could see that being the perfect gateway for rigorous scientists like yourself.

11:59.320 --> 12:03.340
Because I think science in the conventional sense has to be repeatable.

12:03.340 --> 12:09.100
You know, every time you drop this pen, it needs to fall in sort of the same way for it to be science.

12:09.820 --> 12:20.320
And so I think the nuclear link is a version of that with UFOs where UFOs seem to show up across nuclear bases, not only in the U.S., but all over the world.

12:20.760 --> 12:22.440
And that's one thing that worried me.

12:22.520 --> 12:25.920
Once I looked into it, I thought, wow, this is happening in the Soviet Union.

12:26.020 --> 12:27.160
This is happening in France.

12:27.160 --> 12:28.220
This is happening in England.

12:28.220 --> 12:29.780
We were talking before the show.

12:29.900 --> 12:40.460
I'm wearing my American Alchemy Japan shirt, which is paying homage to Lino, which is a town next to their Fukushima prefecture, where they have – they're famous for their nuclear spill in 2011.

12:40.600 --> 12:42.000
They have their civilian energy grid.

12:42.540 --> 12:44.500
And UFOs were reported to show up there.

12:44.600 --> 12:46.220
They have a whole museum dedicated to UFOs.

12:46.940 --> 12:47.120
Right.

12:47.120 --> 12:53.780
And Vice did a documentary on them in 2022, and it's the town in Japan that's obsessed with UFOs, and it's right next to this nuclear grid.

12:53.780 --> 12:58.900
And then I think there was a Netflix Encounter episode, I think episode four, focused on that as well.

12:59.060 --> 13:03.700
And Malmstrom, where you mentioned, that is the site of tons and tons of activity.

13:03.860 --> 13:06.820
You have Bob Salas, obviously, in 67.

13:07.620 --> 13:10.120
But before that, you had this Echo Flight incident.

13:10.520 --> 13:10.620
Right.

13:10.620 --> 13:14.320
You know, I think it was like very – I think it was 10 days before or something.

13:14.420 --> 13:15.480
One was March 16th.

13:15.480 --> 13:16.640
One was March 24th.

13:17.320 --> 13:22.900
Then you have John Mills, this retired missile technician in the early 90s, seeing a bunch of UFOs there.

13:23.280 --> 13:27.360
You even have an interview with this guy, Chris Langan, which – say what you will about the guy.

13:27.500 --> 13:29.240
He says he has the highest IQ in the world.

13:29.320 --> 13:30.480
He seems a little cocky to me.

13:30.680 --> 13:32.080
But he's just offhand.

13:32.240 --> 13:37.020
He's saying he's seen UFOs, and he's seen them around Malmstrom Air Force Base.

13:37.020 --> 13:42.120
On the UFO thing, I was working for the Forest Service, not too far from Malmstrom Air Force Base.

13:42.460 --> 13:47.040
One day, I was up there in a Forest Service pickup truck at a certain campground.

13:47.400 --> 13:52.340
And I was there, and suddenly, I look up, and I say suddenly.

13:52.460 --> 13:53.500
It was just in the skies.

13:53.800 --> 13:56.420
I became aware that it was up there, and I looked up.

13:56.780 --> 14:05.700
There's this huge, spheroidal, you know, but elliptical, not a perfect spheroid, like a saucer that was turned partially on its side.

14:05.940 --> 14:06.140
Right.

14:06.140 --> 14:10.560
And so it's just this recurring trope from all these uncorrelated sources.

14:11.000 --> 14:19.700
Robert Hastings, who wrote the book, UFOs and Nukes, got into this whole subject because his father was actually working at Malmstrom Base.

14:20.140 --> 14:26.540
And he was learning radar theory from one of the radar operators there, Bob Hastings, was while he was a janitor.

14:26.640 --> 14:27.420
He was in high school.

14:27.840 --> 14:31.320
And the radar operator was like, we're tracking some of these unknowns.

14:31.480 --> 14:32.620
You should take a look.

14:32.620 --> 14:34.140
And then that was it for him.

14:34.180 --> 14:37.040
He was hooked, and he dedicated his life to studying this stuff.

14:37.040 --> 14:37.900
That's amazing, yeah.

14:37.940 --> 14:38.940
So, yeah.

14:39.080 --> 14:39.760
Yeah, it's cool.

14:39.960 --> 14:41.780
It was maybe three years ago.

14:41.780 --> 14:46.660
We were down in Louisiana visiting my in-laws for Mardi Gras.

14:47.200 --> 14:51.240
And so it was February, and we're outside grilling, right?

14:51.640 --> 14:58.020
And I was grilling with my wife's Uncle Matt, and he had his Air Force cap on.

14:58.020 --> 15:02.480
And I spotted Malmstrom Air Force Base on his Air Force cap.

15:02.540 --> 15:07.300
And I was like, Uncle Matt, you were in the Air Force, and you were at Malmstrom.

15:07.580 --> 15:08.400
You were at Malmstrom?

15:08.680 --> 15:10.700
And he goes, yeah, I was stationed in Malmstrom.

15:10.880 --> 15:11.780
I go, when were you there?

15:11.800 --> 15:17.360
And he goes, oh, like 1971 through 74, something like that, and early 70s.

15:17.480 --> 15:22.680
And I said, did you ever hear anything about UFO incursions at nuclear weapon sites?

15:22.720 --> 15:24.860
He goes, oh, that happened all the time.

15:25.020 --> 15:27.120
These things would come in and shut down the nuclear weapons.

15:27.120 --> 15:28.640
And he was going on and on about this.

15:28.740 --> 15:31.300
And I'm like, it's common knowledge, right?

15:31.860 --> 15:35.760
And how is it Congress is just finding out about this, right?

15:35.920 --> 15:40.680
And my wife's Uncle Matt has known this since 1971.

15:41.380 --> 15:43.020
This is something to worry about, right?

15:43.220 --> 15:44.360
And I was so excited.

15:44.540 --> 15:50.280
I told him, okay, can you tell my wife this because I'm tired of being the only crazy person in the world?

15:52.560 --> 15:54.700
But his response was amazing.

15:54.820 --> 15:56.260
Oh, yeah, this happened all the time.

15:56.260 --> 15:58.440
And, like, it's nothing, right?

15:58.440 --> 16:10.680
So, on the one hand, you have UFOs showing up around our most important assets or nuclear assets with people who are on the PRP program who literally, like, they have to report if they're on ibuprofen.

16:10.880 --> 16:12.500
These are people who work at the nuclear bases.

16:12.660 --> 16:15.440
So, they're the picture of mental health and of sound mind.

16:15.440 --> 16:20.020
And they all see tic-tacs, saucers, orbs, you know, shutting down nukes.

16:20.400 --> 16:20.420
Right.

16:20.860 --> 16:21.500
There's that.

16:21.600 --> 16:26.160
And then there's the idea that the U.S. government might have saucers and hangers.

16:26.460 --> 16:26.700
Right.

16:27.060 --> 16:30.280
Do you think – it's clear that this is happening, the nuclear thing.

16:30.320 --> 16:30.680
Yeah, yeah.

16:30.680 --> 16:31.120
That's clear.

16:31.180 --> 16:31.940
Absolutely clear, yeah.

16:31.940 --> 16:41.000
Do you think the U.S. government has saucers and hangers and we have an active reverse engineering program for nuts and bolts physical craft?

16:41.340 --> 16:42.400
I think that's probably true.

16:42.580 --> 16:46.840
I've heard this from enough people who've done that kind of work for years now.

16:47.000 --> 16:48.960
That's probably the case, yeah.

16:49.040 --> 16:51.400
Have you met anybody working on the crafts themselves?

16:51.760 --> 16:54.460
I've met people who've claimed to have worked on them or seen them.

16:54.540 --> 16:54.800
Really?

16:54.940 --> 16:55.360
So, yeah.

16:55.720 --> 16:57.660
Anybody that you can mention or –

16:57.660 --> 16:58.760
No, I shouldn't do that.

16:58.820 --> 16:59.120
Okay.

17:00.000 --> 17:02.980
These are whispers that you get every now and again, right?

17:03.000 --> 17:04.520
Did you find them believable, though?

17:04.540 --> 17:05.840
Yeah, entirely believable, yeah.

17:05.840 --> 17:06.140
Really?

17:06.260 --> 17:06.400
Yeah.

17:06.680 --> 17:08.760
No, you didn't sense any sort of deception?

17:09.160 --> 17:09.880
No, no.

17:10.320 --> 17:13.680
One of the most believable things I've heard is, well, have you been able to figure anything out?

17:13.820 --> 17:16.440
No, we don't know what anything is or how anything works.

17:16.640 --> 17:16.980
Yes.

17:17.060 --> 17:19.380
That was my most – and I was like, all right, that makes sense.

17:19.900 --> 17:20.300
Interesting.

17:20.760 --> 17:20.940
Yeah.

17:20.940 --> 17:26.380
So, it's like, you know, giving an iPhone to a caveman or something.

17:26.560 --> 17:27.600
Something like that, yeah.

17:27.760 --> 17:28.160
Interesting.

17:28.280 --> 17:34.520
I mean, it seems like any technologies they've got from it are just, you know, surface level type stuff.

17:34.620 --> 17:35.980
Oh, this is some interesting material.

17:36.080 --> 17:36.740
What's it made of?

17:36.960 --> 17:38.040
That level.

17:38.920 --> 17:43.520
If I were on the inside, I would probably want somebody like you working on this sort of thing.

17:43.600 --> 17:46.460
I would love to be working on this, but not black work.

17:46.540 --> 17:47.820
I'd love to work on this in the open.

17:47.960 --> 17:48.220
Okay.

17:48.220 --> 17:50.600
Have you ever been contacted to do black work?

17:51.520 --> 17:55.440
I had the opportunity to have clearance when I worked at NASA.

17:55.640 --> 17:55.860
Okay.

17:55.940 --> 17:57.120
But I turned it down.

17:57.840 --> 18:00.100
Because you've always wanted to do things in an open, transparent way.

18:00.100 --> 18:08.920
Yeah, I'm a scientist, and I want to – and one of the benefits of being a scientist is we share information, we work together, we cooperate.

18:09.460 --> 18:09.840
Do you think that's –

18:09.840 --> 18:14.700
And, yeah, there's some competition, but there's a lot of collaboration as well, so – and that's very healthy.

18:14.700 --> 18:18.800
Do you think that's part of what's held back, the legacy UFO program?

18:19.320 --> 18:30.780
If it's held back at all, it's because you've got 10 people closeted working on one thing, and they don't get extra information that you might need to get interesting ideas.

18:30.780 --> 18:36.080
You know, the more people you have working on a problem, the more diversity of ideas you're going to get.

18:37.000 --> 18:47.040
Do you think that there are certain scientific things that you can't work on in the kind of civil side, you know, open world of science without receiving backlash?

18:48.540 --> 18:49.580
UFOs is one of them.

18:49.780 --> 18:49.940
Yeah.

18:49.940 --> 18:55.920
Yeah, we – there was some backlash – some backlash when we started working on UFOs.

18:56.240 --> 18:56.800
It was –

18:56.800 --> 19:03.320
You mentioned on Danny Jones that you've had various friends work on anti-gravity and receive sort of backlash.

19:03.940 --> 19:05.980
Threatened threats and things like that, yeah, too.

19:06.120 --> 19:06.800
That's scary.

19:07.200 --> 19:08.420
That's very strange, yeah.

19:08.620 --> 19:11.060
What do you think that is with the anti-gravity stuff?

19:11.060 --> 19:13.220
I really have no idea.

19:13.380 --> 19:21.720
I mean, I – you know, you can jump to conclusions and say, well, because somebody doesn't want other people discovering things that they know about and have control over.

19:21.840 --> 19:26.500
I mean, you could jump to that conclusion, but I don't – I don't actually know what the situation is.

19:26.560 --> 19:27.260
It's hard to tell.

19:27.600 --> 19:29.500
Doesn't that feel like the base case conclusion?

19:29.500 --> 19:41.980
Like, if somebody's getting threatened over discovering a thing, it would seem like there'd be some group on the inside that would be tracking people trying to discover a thing that they're already aware of, right?

19:42.020 --> 19:42.260
Yeah, exactly.

19:42.340 --> 19:44.700
Like, that seems like the Occam's razor easy explanation.

19:44.720 --> 19:47.900
Yeah, I mean, it leads to a whole sets of conspiracy theories, right?

19:47.980 --> 19:48.960
And it's difficult.

19:49.580 --> 19:49.900
Yeah.

19:50.520 --> 19:54.780
Yeah, I've done deep dives on this guy like Townsend Brown, who I'm really fascinated with.

19:54.780 --> 19:58.640
And I talk about him probably too much, but the audience always laughs when I talk.

19:58.860 --> 20:08.820
But, you know, I find him to be really interesting because I do think he made breakthroughs in the world of gravity, this sort of Byfield-Brown effect, which is, I think, a very simple experiment.

20:09.140 --> 20:10.700
