20:39.600 --> 20:42.040
Except at this point, I don't think it's nonsensical.

20:42.260 --> 20:44.240
So, the payoff's huge, right?

20:44.880 --> 20:47.160
How do you think UFOs fly?

20:48.040 --> 20:49.360
I have no idea.

20:49.360 --> 20:53.100
They're very strange in a lot of ways.

20:53.280 --> 20:57.460
First, the – how many ways are they strange, right?

20:59.940 --> 21:04.620
The speeds and accelerations are crazy, right?

21:04.740 --> 21:07.180
The accelerations, nobody's going to survive that.

21:07.520 --> 21:10.840
So, the equipment isn't going to survive it.

21:10.840 --> 21:22.420
So, you know, in the Nimitz case, we estimated the acceleration of the Tic Tac dropping from 28,000 feet to sea level in 0.75 seconds or so, 0.78 seconds.

21:23.580 --> 21:26.920
It's about 5,000 Gs of acceleration minimum, right?

21:27.620 --> 21:29.760
5,000 Gs is insane.

21:29.760 --> 21:35.980
The new F-35 fighter jets, their wings rip off at 13 Gs.

21:36.600 --> 21:44.900
You know, most missile frames can't handle more than – a missile can't maneuver at more than about 35 Gs.

21:44.980 --> 21:48.500
And the frame isn't going to survive more than 60 Gs.

21:48.500 --> 21:52.220
And now you've got this Tic Tac thing accelerating at 5,000 Gs.

21:52.340 --> 21:53.380
That's not possible.

21:53.800 --> 21:55.260
I mean, equipment won't survive.

21:55.680 --> 22:01.880
So, now this leads you to think the only solution there is you've got to be playing with inertia somehow.

22:02.120 --> 22:03.860
You've got to be playing with gravity somehow.

22:04.460 --> 22:10.720
And so, that leads you down the path of general relativity and warp drive and that way of thinking, right?

22:10.720 --> 22:16.080
Do you have, like, a propulsion modality that you like best when it comes to UFOs?

22:16.100 --> 22:17.180
No, I don't exactly.

22:17.540 --> 22:19.480
But then the other problem is power.

22:19.660 --> 22:28.520
If you look at energies and power involved, the amount of power for that Tic Tac dropping is something like – what was it?

22:28.560 --> 22:30.500
It was 1,100 gigawatts of power.

22:31.780 --> 22:37.060
You know, I remember Back to the Future with Doc Brown, 2.1 gigawatts.

22:37.100 --> 22:38.180
Like, that's crazy or something.

22:38.180 --> 22:40.800
This thing was 1,100 gigawatts, right?

22:40.920 --> 22:41.860
I mean, this is –

22:41.860 --> 22:45.360
And he had Mr. Fusion, which was a nuclear fusion machine.

22:45.860 --> 22:46.440
That's right.

22:47.040 --> 22:47.220
Yeah.

22:47.320 --> 22:53.780
So, this is more power – the Tic Tac maneuver took more power than the total nuclear power output of the United States.

22:54.240 --> 22:54.640
Wow.

22:55.220 --> 22:55.460
Wow.

22:55.480 --> 22:58.120
And that's in that Tic Tac in the size of an F-18.

22:58.280 --> 22:59.180
I mean, that's crazy.

22:59.900 --> 23:03.860
And so, now how do you get your head around that?

23:04.860 --> 23:08.100
So, let's say they can deal with that kind of power.

23:08.240 --> 23:11.360
For some reason, they have access to that much energy.

23:13.520 --> 23:15.720
Equipment is never 100% efficient.

23:16.760 --> 23:18.940
So, a 1% inefficiency.

23:19.440 --> 23:24.080
So, most of the things we make are like 20% efficient at best, right?

23:25.080 --> 23:26.620
So, let's say they're really good at this.

23:26.660 --> 23:28.620
They can get to 99% efficiency.

23:28.860 --> 23:31.300
That means you've got a 1% inefficiency.

23:31.880 --> 23:38.100
1% of 1,000 gigawatts is like 11 gigawatts of power.

23:39.060 --> 23:42.420
That means 11 gigawatts of power is going into waste heat.

23:42.420 --> 23:44.520
The thing would melt.

23:45.800 --> 23:46.920
So, now what's happening?

23:47.100 --> 23:49.680
Are they really more efficient than 99%?

23:50.780 --> 23:53.900
Or do we have something wrong?

23:54.140 --> 23:55.840
Are we looking at this the wrong way maybe?

23:55.940 --> 23:59.820
Maybe they're not actually moving in such a way that takes that much power.

23:59.980 --> 24:00.700
