26:59.660 --> 27:04.320
So, he's developed this technique, and he's been working on this furiously for the last couple months.

27:04.420 --> 27:05.340
Neutron activations.

27:05.420 --> 27:07.460
How is that different than mass spec?

27:08.340 --> 27:22.640
Mass spec, you basically, you, typically you dissolve the material in nitric acid, and then you spray it into a, into a, some electric plates that basically electrify it, ionize it.

27:22.640 --> 27:29.080
And then you shoot it into a magnetic field, that constant magnetic field, the thing will move in a circle.

27:29.280 --> 27:31.680
So, and the radius of the circle depends on the mass.

27:31.740 --> 27:36.160
So, then it hits a screen depending on where the mass is, changes where it hits the screen.

27:36.160 --> 27:39.440
So, you can measure the mass of the isotopes inside that spray.

27:39.760 --> 27:46.620
And to back up for the audience, isotope differences are neutron differences in various elements.

27:46.760 --> 27:46.980
Right.

27:47.100 --> 28:00.920
And if you were to find some, you know, isotope ratios in a material that don't occur naturally on Earth and don't pattern match to asteroids, that would be this really exciting, you know, possible smoking gun that the thing is actually a UFO.

28:01.320 --> 28:01.580
Right.

28:01.680 --> 28:02.040
Exactly.

28:02.160 --> 28:02.560
Well said.

28:03.060 --> 28:03.600
Thank you.

28:03.680 --> 28:04.580
Summarized that very nicely.

28:04.580 --> 28:06.360
Yeah, that's exactly it.

28:06.360 --> 28:09.020
And so, Matthew's technique is different.

28:09.300 --> 28:21.640
He basically irradiates the material with neutrons, with a neutron source, and basically creates heavier isotopes with these extra neutrons.

28:22.640 --> 28:29.480
And then he watches them decay back into the states that they were in before.

28:29.480 --> 28:32.140
So, he can tell what the isotopes he created were.

28:32.320 --> 28:36.240
And then he can infer what they were originally from that.

28:36.540 --> 28:43.120
And it's non-destructive because they decay back to where they were pretty quickly.

28:43.940 --> 28:46.800
And you're not doing it to most of the material.

28:46.800 --> 28:55.860
Well, you're only, you know, rating thousands of these atoms rather than, you know, as compared to Avogadro's number for the whole sample, right?

28:56.020 --> 28:56.660
It's so amazing.

