So, so there's a lot of excitement.

51:13.920 --> 51:15.260
There's a lot of excitement in that movie.

51:15.320 --> 51:16.420
And that's real excitement, right?

51:16.640 --> 51:16.900
Yeah.

51:16.900 --> 51:23.420
And, and we did see, we did see some interesting things that, and so here comes some spoilers.

51:24.780 --> 51:27.880
So, and, and so I'm going to spoil things twice.

51:28.100 --> 51:34.600
So, so there's, at one point there's a bright light that's seen from the team in Catalina Island, which was across the Catalina channel.

51:34.720 --> 51:35.720
We had two, two teams.

51:35.720 --> 51:42.160
They spotted this bright light that was moving, and they said, it's too bright to be a satellite.

51:42.540 --> 51:45.040
It's, it's, you know, going in this direction.

51:45.220 --> 51:46.960
So we're, we're looking for it as well.

51:47.220 --> 51:53.200
So we recorded this object, and then it just abruptly disappears, and which is very strange.

51:54.100 --> 52:03.820
And, and the problem with documentaries is that, yes, it takes a long time to make a film, maybe a year to two years in some cases.

52:03.820 --> 52:06.460
Science takes a lot longer.

52:07.360 --> 52:08.500
We're a lot slower.

52:09.500 --> 52:16.640
And so the scientific study of what the data we collected took a lot longer, and that got published just last year.

52:16.720 --> 52:18.420
So our mission was what, in 2021?

52:19.200 --> 52:22.280
Tear in the Sky, I think, came out in 2023, something like that.

52:22.900 --> 52:26.720
And our scientific paper on the mission came out just this summer.

52:28.020 --> 52:31.400
Matthew Shadagas was the first author of that paper.

52:31.400 --> 52:35.460
And so we found that that bright light was the space station.

52:36.960 --> 52:38.780
Why didn't we figure that out earlier?

52:39.080 --> 52:44.080
The app we were using to track satellites didn't take into account daylight savings time.

52:44.480 --> 52:47.420
A stupid mistake, right, that we shouldn't have made.

52:47.560 --> 52:50.440
But this is your first time doing this sort of thing.

52:50.660 --> 52:53.220
And you make, and I remember telling Matthew on our way out.

52:53.220 --> 52:54.840
Space station looks weird, by the way.

52:55.140 --> 52:55.940
And it looks really weird.

52:55.940 --> 52:57.160
It looks like a UFO, yeah.

52:57.160 --> 53:00.520
And I remember telling Matthew on the airplane, you know, we were both excited.

53:00.600 --> 53:01.660
Oh, this is going to be so much fun.

53:01.920 --> 53:03.120
I think, imagine what we can see.

53:03.200 --> 53:08.780
And I said, yeah, but the problem is we're just, what we're probably going to learn is what not to do.

53:09.180 --> 53:09.940
Yeah, yeah, yeah.

53:10.340 --> 53:12.520
And that's really what happened that first mission.

53:12.600 --> 53:13.900
We learned how not to do it.

53:13.900 --> 53:17.780
But Matthew is the one who figured out it was the space station.

53:17.980 --> 53:23.020
He put it all together, and he actually took the pixel size on the camera.

53:23.900 --> 53:29.660
And then, knowing the altitude of the space station, figured out how big the space station should be.

53:29.740 --> 53:34.560
And he was within one foot of the size of the space station.

53:34.860 --> 53:36.440
It's really a nice analysis he does.

53:36.600 --> 53:37.820
He put it in the appendix.

53:37.820 --> 53:46.760
And, yeah, it was something to be proud of, the fact that, yeah, we identified it to be the space station and actually proved it right.

53:47.020 --> 53:47.820
So, that's cool.

53:49.420 --> 53:57.380
Another event that happened was these, one of the FLIR cameras was showing these objects dropping to the sea.

53:57.380 --> 54:03.620
And I was actually, at the time, looking through night vision goggles.

54:03.800 --> 54:08.900
This didn't end up in the movie, and people were too excited about the FLIR camera to hear me shouting about the night.

54:09.160 --> 54:11.980
I was telling people, put on your night vision goggles and look over here.

54:12.620 --> 54:16.540
But I saw something actually drop and hit the water in infrared.

54:16.820 --> 54:17.140
Whoa!

54:17.940 --> 54:18.940
You get that on video?

54:19.260 --> 54:19.940
No, no.

54:19.980 --> 54:22.420
I was just looking through the goggles, watching for things.

54:22.860 --> 54:24.440
But it was through infrared.

54:24.700 --> 54:25.640
It was in infrared, yeah.

54:25.640 --> 54:31.880
And then, and I think they tried to simulate this in the film, but it's not simulated properly.

54:32.020 --> 54:33.960
They showed this thing hovering, and it wasn't, it just dropped.

54:34.080 --> 54:34.480
Wow.

54:34.800 --> 54:39.720
But the FLIR cameras recorded things dropping into the sea, and we...

54:39.720 --> 54:41.200
So, you think you saw a UFO?

54:41.640 --> 54:43.220
I don't know what I saw, actually.

54:43.460 --> 54:48.240
But I was excited because it happened about the same time the FLIR camera was showing things dropping.

54:48.400 --> 54:51.840
But then we figured out later that the FLIR camera was actually malfunctioning.

54:52.300 --> 54:54.420
And that's a failure mode of the FLIR cameras.

54:54.420 --> 54:56.360
We actually talked to the engineers who worked on design on these things.

54:56.360 --> 54:57.400
Is seeing something drop.

54:57.660 --> 55:00.080
Yeah, these things falling down is actually a failure mode.

55:00.200 --> 55:02.940
Oh, so maybe it was an issue with the camera.

55:03.020 --> 55:07.200
So, the FLIR camera recording we had was not something dropping into the sea.

55:08.040 --> 55:13.340
I don't know what I saw, and probably we'll never know, because you can't, it has to be reproducible, right?

55:13.400 --> 55:15.700
You have to be able to see it again and try different things.

55:15.700 --> 55:19.360
Is there a best sensor modality if you're trying to spot UFOs?

55:19.680 --> 55:21.800
I think as many sensors as you can.

55:22.640 --> 55:23.300
Is there one?

55:23.300 --> 55:23.900
Different kinds of...

55:23.900 --> 55:27.760
Say you had to pick one, and you had to, you know, what would you pick?

55:27.900 --> 55:29.360
If I picked one, I would try...

55:29.360 --> 55:30.320
Ugh, that's tough.

55:31.560 --> 55:33.080
I think I would go with...

55:33.080 --> 55:35.480
A FLIR camera is a good choice for a few reasons.

55:36.300 --> 55:38.500
One, you get a visual record of the object.

55:38.640 --> 55:42.760
It's not a very good visual record, because it's going to be blurry, because it's infrared.

55:43.380 --> 55:48.400
I've heard people complain, oh, the Navy produces all these blurry photos of UFOs.

55:48.680 --> 55:49.720
Well, they're infrared images.

55:49.800 --> 55:50.400
What do you expect?

55:51.020 --> 55:54.500
I've heard scientists say this, and you want to slap them upside the head and say,

55:54.700 --> 55:56.100
what did you think was going to happen?

55:56.100 --> 56:04.560
And so, you know, but the other benefit is with a FLIR camera is you can measure the temperature

56:04.560 --> 56:09.620
of the object, because you're picking up infrared emissions, right?

56:09.740 --> 56:14.320
So those, that black body infrared spectrum actually gives you the temperature of the object.

56:14.620 --> 56:16.360
Yeah, where white hot comes from.

56:17.320 --> 56:21.560
Yeah, so not only do you get a visual record of the object, but you get its temperature too,

56:21.700 --> 56:25.060
which is in, you get extra pieces of information for that.

56:25.060 --> 56:27.920
So for that reason, I probably would choose a FLIR can.

56:27.920 --> 56:37.000
Is there a sighting or a crash that you rank as highest conviction, as far as your analysis

56:37.000 --> 56:41.160
of it, that, like, you are convinced that this happened?

56:41.740 --> 56:42.200
Oh.

56:46.160 --> 56:54.920
I would have to say the most convincing one is one of the most hard to believe,

56:55.060 --> 57:00.340
it's JAL 1628.

57:00.340 --> 57:04.720
It was a Japan Airlines cargo flight piloted by Captain Kenju Tarauchi.

57:05.200 --> 57:09.320
This is the sketch Tarauchi drew of what he says he saw in his window that night.

57:09.620 --> 57:12.400
And this Japanese television graphic is based on his description.

57:12.400 --> 57:15.040
This is just a small space ship.

57:15.380 --> 57:18.500
We can see a big frame.

57:18.820 --> 57:22.300
This one is the size of the carrier.

57:22.820 --> 57:23.820
So mothership.

57:23.820 --> 57:27.840
And I, and I remember, I remember that being on the nightly news.

57:27.940 --> 57:32.900
I remember watching, it was on NBC, Tom Brokaw, Connie Chung.

57:33.200 --> 57:39.100
I remember that being on the news and being, holy shit, there's giant aircraft carrier sized

57:39.100 --> 57:44.960
walnut shaped UFO followed that Japanese airlines for 45 minutes across Alaska.

57:45.480 --> 57:45.560
Wild.

57:45.760 --> 57:47.240
Give us the whole sequence.

57:47.240 --> 57:47.600
Yeah.

57:47.780 --> 57:54.120
So these guys, so the Japanese airlines, they, it's a, it's not a passenger jet.

57:54.200 --> 57:54.960
It's a 747.

57:54.960 --> 57:57.880
They are transporting Beaujolais Nouveau.

57:58.220 --> 57:58.500
Yep.

57:58.540 --> 57:59.900
They got wine in the back.

57:59.980 --> 58:01.260
Let the skeptics rejoice.

58:01.640 --> 58:04.520
No, the pilots were not drunk on Beaujolais Nouveau.

58:04.940 --> 58:06.740
It's just a silly thing.

58:07.400 --> 58:08.620
They're just transporting it.

58:08.700 --> 58:08.880
Yeah.

58:08.940 --> 58:10.260
They're just transporting it.

58:10.260 --> 58:17.540
And they're flying across Alaska and, and first, I don't remember all the events and

58:17.540 --> 58:18.360
several things happened.

58:18.440 --> 58:19.820
They actually saw several UFOs.

58:19.940 --> 58:25.220
First, these rectangular things show up in front of the ship and have these lights that

58:25.220 --> 58:27.940
go up and down, shining light into the cockpit.

58:28.760 --> 58:32.220
And the pilots could feel the heat from the light of these objects.

58:32.220 --> 58:36.020
And they're like scanning or, you know, like that kind of behavior.

58:36.020 --> 58:39.860
Um, and they follow in front of the plane for some time.

58:40.440 --> 58:47.280
And then, um, and then this giant walnut shaped object shows up.

58:47.380 --> 58:50.200
That's something like four 747s in length.

58:50.560 --> 58:50.800
Right.

58:50.900 --> 58:53.660
So this thing's, the thing's the size of an aircraft carrier.

58:54.160 --> 58:59.360
And the, the pilot said that when it was in front of the plane, he couldn't see anything

58:59.360 --> 59:00.540
but the craft.

59:01.260 --> 59:02.720
It's that big.

59:02.800 --> 59:03.800
So it's unmistakable.

59:03.800 --> 59:10.340
I mean, and he's screaming at air traffic control, you know, what do I do about this?

59:10.340 --> 59:12.000
And they're not picking it up on radar.

59:12.600 --> 59:18.740
And so, um, it was later found that military height finding radar was picking it up.

59:18.920 --> 59:23.420
And so that radar actually, that, those radar records actually got collected.

59:24.240 --> 59:33.440
And, um, and so this walnut shaped craft basically follow the 747 for about 45 minutes, stayed about

59:33.440 --> 59:37.040
seven kilometers away, but it would go from one side of the plane to the other.

59:37.160 --> 59:39.200
It was bouncing around from one side to the other.

59:39.980 --> 59:50.160
And, um, and we analyzed its speed and acceleration just crudely based on the description of what

59:50.160 --> 59:50.720
it was doing.

59:50.720 --> 59:55.940
So it would go, so at one point it would be at like one o'clock and then the next sweep

59:55.940 --> 59:59.880
of the radar, which was about 12 seconds or so would be, would be at six o'clock.

59:59.880 --> 01:00:06.540
And so we were using those, that information to estimate speeds and accelerations.

01:00:07.200 --> 01:00:13.360
Um, Daniel Kumbay, another, um, physicist from the Niels Bohr Institute actually took the

01:00:13.360 --> 01:00:13.620
radar.

01:00:14.000 --> 01:00:17.740
I didn't, I didn't know that we could get our hands on the radar measurements when we published

01:00:17.740 --> 01:00:21.920
that paper, but he actually got the radar data and he analyzed that.

01:00:22.000 --> 01:00:27.080
He was analyzing the jumps and he found that the object was accelerating at, took several

01:00:27.080 --> 01:00:31.880
dumps, jumps, different accelerations at different times, but there were three, three of them

01:00:31.880 --> 01:00:36.200
were, the accelerations were greater than 9,000 Gs.

01:00:37.460 --> 01:00:44.200
One of them was like 11,000 Gs and the top speed he estimated to be 250,000 miles an hour.

01:00:45.660 --> 01:00:50.120
And at 250,000 miles an hour, you can get to the moon in 54 minutes.

01:00:50.800 --> 01:00:51.240
Whoa.

01:00:51.900 --> 01:00:53.340
That's, that's not a joke.

01:00:53.340 --> 01:00:59.900
So you've got something the size of an aircraft carrier that could get to the moon in less

01:00:59.900 --> 01:01:00.780
than an hour, right?

01:01:00.820 --> 01:01:02.860
That's basically what you've, you're dealing with here.

01:01:03.100 --> 01:01:06.240
So that's what, and we have, and we have the radar data from that.

01:01:06.480 --> 01:01:07.620
We have the radar data.

01:01:07.720 --> 01:01:08.620
You have the radar data.

01:01:08.680 --> 01:01:09.240
That's amazing.

01:01:09.320 --> 01:01:09.780
I didn't know that.

01:01:09.800 --> 01:01:10.280
That's amazing.

01:01:10.360 --> 01:01:10.540
Yeah.

01:01:10.660 --> 01:01:17.740
John Callahan, who was the FAA chief of accidents and investigations actually reviewed the case.

01:01:17.740 --> 01:01:25.300
And then Reagan, President Reagan's scientific team and the CIA showed up and they wanted

01:01:25.300 --> 01:01:25.940
all the data.

01:01:26.260 --> 01:01:26.620
No way.

01:01:26.840 --> 01:01:28.600
And so they came to collect the data.

01:01:29.140 --> 01:01:34.480
Callahan copied it and put it in a box that he just put under his desk.

01:01:35.620 --> 01:01:39.120
And so he had a copy of it and he didn't turn that over.

01:01:39.680 --> 01:01:40.680
So they got.

01:01:40.800 --> 01:01:41.760
And that's public now?

01:01:41.940 --> 01:01:42.920
And now that's public.

01:01:43.060 --> 01:01:43.320
Whoa.

01:01:43.320 --> 01:01:45.220
He held onto it for like 20 years.

01:01:45.360 --> 01:01:47.220
And then when he retired, he made it public.

01:01:47.240 --> 01:01:47.900
Good for him.

01:01:48.100 --> 01:01:48.360
Yeah.

01:01:48.460 --> 01:01:49.340
He's a hero, right?

01:01:49.500 --> 01:01:49.880
Kind of.

01:01:50.100 --> 01:01:50.360
Yeah.

01:01:50.880 --> 01:01:51.100
Yeah.

01:01:51.260 --> 01:01:54.880
But he said, so when he was in the meeting with Reagan's scientific team, they were all

01:01:54.880 --> 01:01:55.160
excited.

01:01:55.260 --> 01:01:59.240
They said, we've never had 45 minutes of radar data from one of these things before.

01:01:59.660 --> 01:02:00.060
Wow.

01:02:00.160 --> 01:02:02.820
And so, so that exists.

01:02:02.820 --> 01:02:09.200
But, but from that radar data, it's accelerating at 10,000 Gs, 250,000 miles an hour.

01:02:09.520 --> 01:02:12.960
And, and you can actually see the position of the plane on the radar.

01:02:12.960 --> 01:02:13.880
That is remarkable.

01:02:13.880 --> 01:02:18.340
And at the one point where the plane actually does a 360 to try to shake this thing, you

01:02:18.340 --> 01:02:19.560
can actually see that on the radar.

01:02:19.680 --> 01:02:20.580
So the radar is working.

01:02:21.140 --> 01:02:22.400
Are the pilots still alive?

01:02:22.740 --> 01:02:23.520
Yeah, I think so.

01:02:23.700 --> 01:02:24.860
I want to get in touch with that.

01:02:24.900 --> 01:02:25.560
Yeah, I'm sure.

01:02:25.880 --> 01:02:27.460
The one pilot was actually fired.

01:02:27.820 --> 01:02:28.120
Okay.

01:02:28.320 --> 01:02:29.700
For going public with it.

01:02:29.820 --> 01:02:32.540
He was fired and had his license taken away.

01:02:32.620 --> 01:02:35.300
And then several years later, it was reinstated.

01:02:35.420 --> 01:02:37.880
That's horrible that he was fired for that.

01:02:37.880 --> 01:02:42.660
I mean, what are you supposed to, you experienced something that kind of traumatic and worldview

01:02:42.660 --> 01:02:43.320
shattering.

01:02:43.720 --> 01:02:47.280
What would lying about it be a better thing to do for flight safety?

01:02:47.640 --> 01:02:48.080
Yeah, right.

01:02:48.360 --> 01:02:49.520
That's really the question.

01:02:49.640 --> 01:02:50.400
Just ignore it.

01:02:50.480 --> 01:02:51.400
Yeah, that's crazy.

01:02:52.360 --> 01:02:52.840
Fascinating.

01:02:52.920 --> 01:02:58.800
You know, there's that audio recording of Steven Spielberg, I believe, talking about his

01:02:58.800 --> 01:02:59.940
trip to the White House.

01:03:00.420 --> 01:03:02.640
And they do a viewing of E.T.

01:03:02.780 --> 01:03:03.220
Oh, right.

01:03:03.220 --> 01:03:03.840
I've heard this.

01:03:03.920 --> 01:03:04.140
Yes.

01:03:04.400 --> 01:03:10.380
And Reagan says, you know, a lot of you in this room know that everything on that screen

01:03:10.380 --> 01:03:12.220
there that you just watched is true.

01:03:12.380 --> 01:03:15.940
And he just stood up and he looked around the room, almost like he was doing a head

01:03:15.940 --> 01:03:16.240
count.

01:03:16.740 --> 01:03:20.700
And he said, I want to thank you for bringing E.T. to the White House.

01:03:20.780 --> 01:03:21.920
We really enjoyed your movie.

01:03:21.920 --> 01:03:26.100
And then he looked around the room and he said, and there are a number of people in this

01:03:26.100 --> 01:03:29.340
room who know that everything on that screen is absolutely true.

01:03:29.500 --> 01:03:30.900
And he said it without smiling.

01:03:30.900 --> 01:03:34.620
But he said that.

01:03:34.700 --> 01:03:35.820
And everybody laughed, by the way.

01:03:35.860 --> 01:03:39.540
The whole room laughed because he presented it like a joke, but he wasn't smiling as he

01:03:39.540 --> 01:03:39.960
said it.

01:03:40.240 --> 01:03:42.640
And so, yeah, it's pretty interesting, right?

01:03:42.660 --> 01:03:43.480
It's interesting, right?

01:03:43.600 --> 01:03:44.000
Yeah.

01:03:44.220 --> 01:03:48.660
Well, that's fascinating that people from his scientific team, I mean, it sounds like they

01:03:48.660 --> 01:03:53.560
were pretty aware of this to say, oh, we've never had 45 minutes.

01:03:53.740 --> 01:03:59.240
But it's like, that implies, OK, you're sitting on maybe, you know, shorter clips of UFOs.

01:03:59.240 --> 01:04:00.620
Yeah, they've got something.

01:04:00.760 --> 01:04:01.520
They've got something.

01:04:01.840 --> 01:04:02.100
Yeah.

01:04:02.640 --> 01:04:06.760
I mean, Alaska is a hotspot historically as well.

01:04:06.840 --> 01:04:11.460
I believe Nathan Twining, who's head of Air Material Command, responsible for all aircraft

01:04:11.460 --> 01:04:17.620
development of the Air Force, wrote the famous Twining memo in 1947 saying UFOs are not visionary

01:04:17.620 --> 01:04:18.500
nor fictitious.

01:04:18.760 --> 01:04:19.000
Right.

01:04:19.000 --> 01:04:24.460
He, I believe they had like an observation program going on in Alaska.

01:04:24.620 --> 01:04:28.980
And then just recently you had, it was this weird sequence of events, but in 2020, early

01:04:28.980 --> 01:04:31.260
2023, you had the Chinese spy balloon.

01:04:31.720 --> 01:04:37.240
And then right after that, you had this bizarre, you know, these things seem to show up and like

01:04:37.240 --> 01:04:41.360
jam, you know, the radars of these F-22s.

01:04:41.360 --> 01:04:44.860
And one of them specifically was in Alaska and crashed.

01:04:45.140 --> 01:04:50.920
And I've heard some very strange things around this specific craft.

01:04:51.140 --> 01:04:56.100
I've heard things like it reassembled itself and was seen in the air over Canada.

01:04:57.100 --> 01:04:57.660
Bizarre.

01:04:57.660 --> 01:05:02.300
I've heard something, I've heard something about deleted emails involving this specific

01:05:02.300 --> 01:05:06.340
craft, uh, in the National Military Command Center servers.

01:05:06.760 --> 01:05:08.040
So I don't know.

01:05:08.100 --> 01:05:12.940
It seems like there's something strange about this craft and this, this was also in Alaska.

01:05:13.300 --> 01:05:13.320
So.

01:05:13.400 --> 01:05:13.560
Right.

01:05:13.720 --> 01:05:14.080
Who knows?

01:05:14.340 --> 01:05:14.920
That's amazing.

01:05:15.180 --> 01:05:15.460
Yeah.

01:05:15.860 --> 01:05:16.260
Yeah.

01:05:16.760 --> 01:05:17.160
Yeah.

01:05:17.160 --> 01:05:22.060
It's amazing to know that, you know, his scientific, Reagan scientific team had gotten that data.

01:05:22.200 --> 01:05:23.100
What did they do with it?

01:05:23.140 --> 01:05:25.480
What is, you know, what are, where are their reports?

01:05:25.480 --> 01:05:30.200
I would like to see that, you know, the, you know, disclose those.

01:05:30.420 --> 01:05:32.000
That would be interesting, you know, alone.

01:05:32.260 --> 01:05:40.500
Um, the Kecksburg, Pennsylvania UFO crash.

01:05:40.700 --> 01:05:41.020
Yeah.

01:05:41.180 --> 01:05:41.700
1965.

01:05:42.340 --> 01:05:42.780
Yeah.

01:05:42.860 --> 01:05:49.040
And my, my dad's cousin, Donald Hornig, he was later the president of Brown University was,

01:05:49.240 --> 01:05:55.460
was on, he was the scientific advisor to President Eisenhower.

01:05:55.480 --> 01:05:56.700
Kennedy and Johnson.

01:05:56.940 --> 01:05:57.280
What?

01:05:57.540 --> 01:05:57.780
Yeah.

01:05:57.840 --> 01:05:59.440
